tree.node

Class ProductTreeNode

  • java.lang.Object
    • tree.node.GenericTreeNode<IProduct>
      • tree.node.ProductTreeNode
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    IDeepCopy, ITreeNode<IProduct>, ISearchableByFilter<ITreeNode<IProduct>>

    public class ProductTreeNode
extends GenericTreeNode<IProduct>
    This class is used for ITreeNodes with IProducts as values in an ITree. It extends the GenericTreeNode class. It binds the typeparameter NODETYPE of GenericTreeNode to IProduct. This means that the ProductTreeNode only allows IProduct values.
    Author:
    OOP

    • Constructor Detail

      • ProductTreeNode

        public ProductTreeNode(String label,
                       IProduct value)
        Constructor of the ProductTreeNode that takes two arguments (label and value) and initializes the object accordingly. If the passed value is of type JointProduct then a list of child ITreeNodes is initialized using this JointProduct. Each Product referenced in the JointProduct is used to create a new ProductTreeNode. This is applied recursively on all referenced Products. In any other case an empty Collection is used to initialize the child ITreeNodes.
        Parameters:
        label - The label of the ProductTreeNode
        value - The IProduct value object for the ProductTreeNode

      • ProductTreeNode

        public ProductTreeNode(IProduct value)
        Constructor of the ProductTreeNode that takes one argument (value) and initializes the object accordingly. IProduct.getName() is used as a label. If the passed value is of type JointProduct then a list of child ITreeNodes is initialized using this JointProduct. Each Product referenced in the JointProduct is used to create a new ProductTreeNode. This is applied recursively on all reference Products. In any other case an empty Collection is used to initialize the child ITreeNodes.
        Parameters:
        value - The IProduct value object for the ProductTreeNode

      • toString

        public String toString()
        Description copied from class: java.lang.Object
        Returns a string representation of the object. In general, the toString method returns a string that "textually represents" this object. The result should be a concise but informative representation that is easy for a person to read. It is recommended that all subclasses override this method.

        The toString method for class Object returns a string consisting of the name of the class of which the object is an instance, the at-sign character `@', and the unsigned hexadecimal representation of the hash code of the object. In other words, this method returns a string equal to the value of: 

         getClass().getName() + '@' + Integer.toHexString(hashCode())

      • deepCopy

        public ProductTreeNode deepCopy()
        Creates a copy of the GenericTreeNode and all its attributes and returns it. All attributes that implement the IDeepCopy interface have to be copied via the IDeepCopy.deepCopy() method as well. This means that also all direct child ITreeNodes which implement the IDeepCopy interface have to be copied via the IDeepCopy.deepCopy() method.

        Redefined here to limit the return type of the IDeepCopy.deepCopy() method to ITreeNode.

        Creates and returns a copy of this object. The precise meaning of "copy" may depend on the class of the object. The general intent is that, for any object x, the expression: 

         x.deepCopy() != x
        will be true, and that the expression: 
         x.deepCopy().getClass() == x.getClass()
        will be true, but these are not absolute requirements. While it is typically the case that: 
         x.deepCopy().equals(x)
        will be true, this is not an absolute requirement.

        In addition, the value of the ProductTreeNode has to be copied via the IDeepCopy.deepCopy() method as well since IProduct extends IDeepCopy.

        HINT: try to use casting if problems occur. In any case you might encounter a warning UnsafeCast even if you have checked before casting. This can be ignored.
